---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import RelatedProducts from '../../components/RelatedProducts.astro';
import WWPointsCalculator from '../../components/WWPointsCalculator.astro';
---

<BaseLayout
  title="Costco Hot Dog Weight Watchers Points"
  description="How many Weight Watchers SmartPoints is a Costco hot dog? Interactive calculator with bun, condiments, and modifications."
  type="article"
  publishedAt="2026-04-29"
>
  <article class="max-w-4xl mx-auto px-4 sm:px-6 lg:px-8 py-12">
    <h1 class="text-4xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Costco Hot Dog Weight Watchers Points</h1>
    <p class="text-lg text-gray-600 mb-8">Calculate SmartPoints for your Costco hot dog with our interactive calculator. Adjust for bun, condiments, and toppings.</p>

    <div class="bg-blue-50 border border-blue-200 rounded-xl p-6 mb-8">
      <h2 class="text-xl font-bold text-blue-900 mb-2">Quick Answer</h2>
      <p class="text-blue-800 text-lg">
        A standard Costco hot dog <strong>with bun</strong> is <strong class="text-2xl">14 SmartPoints</strong> on the Weight Watchers program.
        Without the bun, it drops to <strong>10 SmartPoints</strong>.
      </p>
    </div>

    <WWPointsCalculator />

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Understanding WW SmartPoints</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      Weight Watchers SmartPoints are calculated based on calories, saturated fat, sugar, and protein content. Foods higher in protein get a slight discount, while foods high in sugar and saturated fat cost more points.
    </p>
    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-6 leading-relaxed">
      The Costco hot dog scores relatively high on SmartPoints primarily due to its calorie density and saturated fat content. However, it also delivers a solid 24g of protein, which helps offset the point value slightly.
    </p>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Points Breakdown by Component</h2>
    <div class="bg-white rounded-xl shadow-sm border border-gray-200 overflow-hidden mb-8">
      <table class="w-full">
        <thead class="bg-gray-50">
          <tr>
            <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left text-sm font-semibold">Component</th>
            <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left text-sm font-semibold">SmartPoints</th>
            <th class="px-6 py-3 text-left text-sm font-semibold">Notes</th>
          </tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody class="divide-y divide-gray-200">
          <tr>
            <td class="px-6 py-3 font-medium">Hot dog (meat only)</td>
            <td class="px-6 py-3 font-bold text-blue-700">10</td>
            <td class="px-6 py-3 text-gray-600">High protein, high fat</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="px-6 py-3 font-medium">Bun</td>
            <td class="px-6 py-3 font-bold text-blue-700">4</td>
            <td class="px-6 py-3 text-gray-600">Refined carbohydrates</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="px-6 py-3 font-medium">Mustard</td>
            <td class="px-6 py-3 font-bold text-blue-700">0</td>
            <td class="px-6 py-3 text-gray-600">Negligible calories</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="px-6 py-3 font-medium">Ketchup</td>
            <td class="px-6 py-3 font-bold text-blue-700">0</td>
            <td class="px-6 py-3 text-gray-600">Small portion size</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="px-6 py-3 font-medium">Relish</td>
            <td class="px-6 py-3 font-bold text-blue-700">1</td>
            <td class="px-6 py-3 text-gray-600">Added sugars</td>
          </tr>
          <tr>
            <td class="px-6 py-3 font-medium">Onions</td>
            <td class="px-6 py-3 font-bold text-blue-700">0</td>
            <td class="px-6 py-3 text-gray-600">Zero-point vegetable</td>
          </tr>
        </tbody>
      </table>
    </div>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Tips for Lowering Your Points</h2>
    <ul class="list-disc list-inside space-y-2 text-gray-700 mb-8">
      <li><strong>Skip the bun</strong> — saves 4 points instantly. Ask for the hot dog "naked."</li>
      <li><strong>Load up on onions</strong> — they're a zero-point food and add flavor and crunch.</li>
      <li><strong>Avoid relish</strong> — the added sugars cost 1 point. Mustard and ketchup are free.</li>
      <li><strong>Share the combo</strong> — split the hot dog with a friend and bank the remaining weekly points.</li>
      <li><strong>Pair with water</strong> — the included soda adds empty calories. Opt for water to stay on track.</li>
    </ul>

    <h2 class="text-2xl font-bold text-gray-900 mb-4">Is It Worth the Points?</h2>
    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-4 leading-relaxed">
      At 14 SmartPoints, the Costco hot dog combo uses a significant portion of most people's daily budget (typically 23-30 points). However, at just $1.50, it's one of the most affordable high-protein meals available.
    </p>
    <p class="text-gray-700 mb-8 leading-relaxed">
      Many WW members treat the Costco hot dog as an occasional indulgence rather than a regular meal. If you plan ahead and budget your points, you can absolutely enjoy this iconic combo without derailing your progress.
    </p>

    <RelatedProducts category="Health" title="Weight Management Products" />
  </article>
</BaseLayout>
